{"word":"προσέοικα","slug":"προσέοικα","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>προσέοικα</b></el> <el>(<a href='S:perfect tense'>perf.</a> with <a href='S:present tense'>pres.</a> sense) </el><br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b>no <a href='S:present tense'>pres.</a> <el>προσείκω</el> is in use\n<el>(attic <a href='S:infinitive'>inf.</a> <el>προσεικέναι</el>) (doric plup. <el>ποτῴκειν</el>) (2nd sg. <a href='S:perfect tense'>perf.</a> <a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>pass.</a></a> <el>προσήιξαι</el>) </el><p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b>in <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b>:— <i>to be like, resemble</i>, <a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:dative'>dat.</a>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b><i>to seem fit</i>, <el>τὰ μὴ προσεικότα</el> <i>things not fit and seemly</i>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>; so, <el>οὐκ ἐμοὶ προσεικότα</el> <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>III. </b><i>to seem</i> to do, <a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:infinitive'>inf.</a>, <b><a href='S:Demosthenes'>Dem.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}